<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910418-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>910418-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Orders Agencies   To Pare Energy Use   20% by the Year 2000</HL><DATE>04/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- President Bush ordered federal agencies toreduce their energy use 20% by the year 2000 from 1985levels.   In an executive order, the president also is requiring theagencies to cut oil used in motor vehicles 10% by 1995,compared with 1991 levels, and to make wider use ofnon-gasoline fuels. He told a cabinet meeting that he hopedthe federal action would &quot;encourage the private sector toundertake similar actions.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The president's national energy legislation, which ispending in Congress, seeks to reduce oil consumption andwould require increased use of alternative-fuel vehicles inprivate-sector fleets, among other provisions. This week, theSenate Energy Committee has begun voting on its own energymeasure.   Mr. Bush said the steps will save taxpayers $800 millionannually in energy costs by 2000 and conserve the equivalentof 100,000 barrels of oil a day. The federal governmentalready is required by law to cut energy use in buildings 10%by 1995.   In addition, the executive order requires reductions atfederal industrial facilities. Federal agencies also will berequired to buy energy-efficient products and participate inutility conservation programs.</TEXT></DOC>